ncy.\n\nI need to examine whether my test description actually demands System level or if it could pass at a lower one. The description doesn't explicitly require real git subprocess calls—it could theoretically work with mocked git responses at Integration level. But the intent seems to be testing real tool behavior against realistic repository states.\n\nFor the rename detection test, System level is genuinely necessary since I need real git to properly detect file renames. Mocking git's output at Integration level wouldn't validate that the tool correctly interprets actual rename detection. The test requires real git behavior to be meaningful.\n\nLooking at the subprocess definitions more carefully: System tests involve actual subprocess calls to external tools, while Integration tests can mock those calls. Since my test descriptions say \"run the tool\" and \"create a repository\" without specifying mocks, I need to determine whether each test truly requires real git or can work with mocked responses. For rename detection specifically, I can't adequately test the feature without invoking real git against an actual repository with renamed files.\n\nBinary file handling similarly demands real git to properly validate the tool's behavior in genuine scenarios. The empty repository case is different—I could mock git's \"no commits\" response and verify the tool handles it correctly, making this an integration-level test. For counting accuracy across various scenarios, constructing reliable mock outputs becomes complex, so using real git provides better confidence. Staged versus unstaged changes present a similar challenge where mocking could work in theory, but verifying the tool's actual behavior requires testing against real git state.\n\nLooking back at my assessments, they seem justified. Now I should check whether my test descriptions actually align with the levels I assigned. The renamed files test explicitly describes creating a git repository and renaming a file in a new commit—these operations inherently require real git, not mocks, so the system-level classification holds. For binary files, the description similarly calls for creating a test repository and modifying binary files across commits, which again necessitates actual git operations rather than mocked output.\n\nThe empty repository test is different—it only requires initializing a repo structure without any commits, which can be done at the integration level with local filesystem setup. The count accuracy test demands a sequence of real commits, and the staged vs unstaged test requires actual git staging operations, both confirming system-level testing is appropriate.\n\nAll five tests align with their assigned levels. Now I can prepare the final structured output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13324,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13324},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5987409f-f776-4fae-a9bf-65e355092356","uuid":"df7c887d-0e92-48ec-a71a-11fa1533fb0c"}
